          <h2>Introduction to White Dwarf Stars</h2>
          <p>White dwarf stars represent one of the most fascinating end states of stellar evolution. These extraordinarily dense objects are the exposed cores of <a href="/atlas/stars/main-sequence/">main sequence</a> stars that have exhausted their nuclear fuel, shed their outer layers, and ceased all fusion reactions. What remains is a stellar corpse supported not by the energy of nuclear fusion, but by a quantum mechanical pressure that defies further gravitational collapse.</p>

          <p>The name "white dwarf" describes their appearance: they are initially white-hot (with surface temperatures that can exceed 100,000 K when first formed) and dwarf-sized (roughly the diameter of Earth). Despite their small size, white dwarfs typically contain between 0.5 and 1.4 solar masses worth of material—imagine squeezing half the Sun into an object the size of our planet. This creates matter in an exotic state called "degenerate matter," with densities around one million times that of water.</p>

          <p>White dwarfs are incredibly common in the universe. Approximately 97% of all stars—including our Sun—will end their lives as white dwarfs. The nearest white dwarf is Sirius B, the faint companion to Sirius (the brightest star in our night sky), located just 8.6 light-years away. As the universe ages, white dwarfs will become increasingly prevalent, eventually dominating the stellar population as more and more stars exhaust their fuel and die.</p>

          <p>These stellar remnants play crucial roles in modern astronomy. White dwarfs in binary systems can explode as Type Ia supernovae—events so consistent in brightness that they serve as "standard candles" for measuring cosmic distances. They also serve as cosmic laboratories for studying matter under extreme conditions that cannot be replicated on Earth.</p>
