          <h2>Physical Characteristics</h2>
          <p>White dwarfs are objects of extraordinary extremes—small, dense, hot, and unlike any form of matter we encounter in everyday life. Their physical properties challenge our intuitions about matter and gravity.</p>

          <div class="info-box glass">
            <h3>White Dwarf Typical Properties</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Radius:</strong> ~7,000 km (similar to Earth; about 1/100th the Sun's radius)</li>
              <li><strong>Mass:</strong> 0.5-1.4 solar masses (typically 0.6 solar masses)</li>
              <li><strong>Surface Temperature:</strong> 8,000-40,000 K (initially; can exceed 100,000 K when first formed)</li>
              <li><strong>Density:</strong> ~1,000,000 g/cm³ (1 million times water; 1 teaspoon = 5 tons)</li>
              <li><strong>Surface Gravity:</strong> ~350,000 times Earth's gravity</li>
              <li><strong>Luminosity:</strong> 0.0001-1 solar luminosity (decreases with age)</li>
              <li><strong>Color:</strong> White to blue-white when young; yellow/red when older</li>
              <li><strong>Composition:</strong> Typically carbon-oxygen core; some helium or ONeMg</li>
              <li><strong>Support Mechanism:</strong> Electron degeneracy pressure (not thermal pressure)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <h3>Extreme Density</h3>
          <p>The defining characteristic of white dwarfs is their extraordinary density. A typical white dwarf packs about 0.6 solar masses into a sphere roughly the size of Earth. This creates matter in a state called "degenerate matter" with densities around 1 million grams per cubic centimeter—a teaspoon of white dwarf material would weigh about 5 tons on Earth. At these densities, atoms are crushed so tightly that electrons are stripped from their nuclei and packed together as densely as quantum mechanics permits.</p>

          <h3>Small but Massive</h3>
          <p>White dwarfs are remarkably small for their mass. A typical white dwarf has a radius of about 7,000 kilometers—slightly smaller than Earth (12,742 km diameter). Despite this compact size, it contains roughly the Sun's mass. This creates surface gravity hundreds of thousands of times stronger than Earth's. If you could somehow stand on a white dwarf's surface, you'd be crushed by gravity about 350,000 times stronger than what you experience on Earth.</p>

          <h3>Hot but Faint</h3>
          <p>White dwarfs are initially extremely hot—surface temperatures can range from 8,000 K for cooler examples to over 40,000 K for freshly exposed cores (some can even exceed 100,000 K initially). Despite these high temperatures, white dwarfs are faint. Their small surface area means they radiate far less total energy than a <a href="/atlas/stars/main-sequence/">main sequence</a> star of similar temperature. A typical white dwarf might have only 0.01% of the Sun's luminosity.</p>

          <h3>The Mass-Radius Inverse Relationship</h3>
          <p>White dwarfs exhibit a counterintuitive property: more massive white dwarfs are smaller than less massive ones. This is because they're supported by electron degeneracy pressure, which increases with density. To support a larger mass against gravity, the matter must be compressed to higher density, reducing the radius. The most massive white dwarfs (approaching the Chandrasekhar limit of 1.4 solar masses) are only about half the radius of the least massive ones.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Formation -->
        <section id="formation" class="content-section">
          <h2>Formation from Planetary Nebulae</h2>
          <p>White dwarfs are born from the deaths of <a href="/atlas/stars/red-giants/">red giant</a> stars in a beautiful process involving planetary nebulae. Understanding this formation process reveals the final fate awaiting most stars in the universe, including our Sun.</p>

          <h3>The Red Giant Prelude</h3>
          <p>The journey to becoming a white dwarf begins when a <a href="/atlas/stars/main-sequence/">main sequence</a> star exhausts the hydrogen in its core. The star expands dramatically into a <a href="/atlas/stars/red-giants/">red giant</a>, fusing hydrogen in a shell around an inert helium core. Eventually, the core becomes hot enough to fuse helium into carbon and oxygen via the triple-alpha process. For stars like the Sun (between 0.5 and 8 solar masses), this is as far as nuclear fusion proceeds—the core never becomes hot or massive enough to fuse carbon.</p>

          <h3>The Asymptotic Giant Branch</h3>
          <p>After helium exhaustion, the star enters the asymptotic giant branch (AGB) phase, its second and final red giant stage. Now the star has a carbon-oxygen core surrounded by shells of helium and hydrogen fusion. The star becomes extremely luminous but unstable, experiencing thermal pulses and losing mass prodigiously via powerful stellar winds. Over time, the star ejects much of its envelope into space, losing up to half its mass.</p>

          <h3>Planetary Nebula Formation</h3>
          <p>As the AGB star loses its outer layers, the hot core becomes increasingly exposed. The intense ultraviolet radiation from the core (now reaching temperatures of 30,000-100,000 K) ionizes the previously ejected gas, causing it to glow as a planetary nebula—a beautiful, expanding shell of glowing gas surrounding the dying star. This phase lasts only about 10,000-20,000 years, a cosmic eyeblink.</p>

          <h3>The White Dwarf Emerges</h3>
          <p>Once the envelope is completely ejected, all that remains is the exposed stellar core—the newborn white dwarf. This remnant is initially blazing hot (often exceeding 100,000 K at the surface) but incredibly small and faint. With no remaining hydrogen or helium fuel to burn, and insufficient mass to fuse its carbon-oxygen composition, nuclear fusion has permanently ceased. The white dwarf phase has begun, and the star will now spend trillions of years simply cooling off.</p>

          <h3>Formation Timeline</h3>
          <p>For a Sun-like star, the entire process from main sequence to white dwarf takes about 11-12 billion years: 10 billion years on the main sequence, 1-2 billion years as a red giant (including the AGB phase), and finally the transition through the planetary nebula phase. More massive stars evolve faster, potentially becoming white dwarfs in less than 100 million years total.</p>
        </section>

