        <section id="examples" class="content-section">
          <h2>Notable White Dwarf Stars</h2>
          <p>While white dwarfs are faint and difficult to observe, several have become famous due to their proximity, unusual properties, or associations with bright companion stars.</p>

          <h3>Sirius B</h3>
          <p>Sirius B is the most famous white dwarf, companion to Sirius A, the brightest star in our night sky. Located just 8.6 light-years away, Sirius B orbits Sirius A every 50 years. It has about 1 solar mass compressed into an Earth-sized volume, with a surface temperature around 25,000 K. Despite being about as massive as the Sun, Sirius B is 10,000 times fainter than its brilliant companion.</p>

          <p>Sirius B was historically significant. In 1844, astronomer Friedrich Bessel noted that Sirius A appeared to wobble, suggesting an unseen companion. Sirius B was finally observed in 1862 by telescope maker Alvan Graham Clark. When astronomers later measured its mass and realized it was comparable to the Sun despite being far fainter, it became the first recognized white dwarf—though the physics of degenerate matter wouldn't be understood until the 1920s.</p>

          <h3>Procyon B</h3>
          <p>Procyon B is the white dwarf companion to Procyon A, the eighth-brightest star in the night sky. Located 11.5 light-years away, Procyon B orbits its main sequence companion every 41 years. It has about 0.6 solar masses and a surface temperature around 7,740 K, making it cooler than Sirius B. Its relatively low temperature suggests it's older, having had more time to cool. Like Sirius B, Procyon B was detected through its gravitational influence on its companion before being observed directly.</p>

          <h3>40 Eridani B</h3>
          <p>40 Eridani B holds the distinction of being the first white dwarf whose nature was understood. This white dwarf is part of a triple star system located 16.5 light-years away. It orbits a main sequence star (40 Eridani A) along with a red dwarf companion (40 Eridani C). Discovered in 1783, 40 Eridani B was identified as a white dwarf in 1910 when its spectrum revealed it to be both very hot and very faint—properties that only made sense if it were extremely small and dense.</p>

          <h3>Van Maanen's Star</h3>
          <p>Van Maanen's Star, located 14.1 light-years away, is the closest solitary white dwarf to Earth. Discovered in 1917 by Dutch-American astronomer Adriaan van Maanen, it has a mass of about 0.68 solar masses and a surface temperature around 6,100 K. Its relatively cool temperature indicates significant age—estimates suggest it's about 3-4 billion years old. Van Maanen's Star is also notable for showing evidence of having accreted rocky material, likely from disrupted asteroids or planets, making it one of many white dwarfs with polluted atmospheres.</p>

          <h3>WD 1856+534</h3>
          <p>In 2020, astronomers announced the discovery of a Jupiter-sized planet orbiting the white dwarf WD 1856+534, located about 80 light-years away. This was remarkable because planets are usually destroyed when their host stars expand into <a href="/atlas/stars/red-giants/">red giants</a>. The planet's survival suggests it formed farther out and migrated inward after the white dwarf formed, or somehow survived the red giant phase. This discovery has profound implications for understanding planetary system evolution and the fate of planets around dying stars.</p>

          <h3>IK Pegasi B</h3>
          <p>IK Pegasi B is the nearest known Type Ia supernova progenitor candidate, located about 150 light-years away. This white dwarf has a mass estimated at 1.15 solar masses and is accreting material from its companion, a main sequence star. In the far future—likely 5-6 billion years from now—IK Pegasi B may reach the Chandrasekhar limit and explode as a Type Ia supernova. When that happens, it will briefly become one of the brightest objects in our sky, though at 150 light-years it poses no danger to Earth.</p>
        </section>

